@sen221    To give one instance out of several which I have observed: I crossed some white fantails, which breed very true, with some black barbs--and it so happens that blue varieties of barbs are so rare that I never heard of an instance in England; and the mongrels were black, brown and mottled.

              " (extract-fr) part 4 of  about: each other, domestic breeds, other cases, geographical sub-species, wild state, from the rock-pigeon

@sen222    I also crossed a barb with a spot, which is a white bird with a red tail and red spot on the forehead, and which notoriously breeds very true; the mongrels were dusky and mottled.

              " (extract-fr) part 4 of  about: each other, domestic breeds, other cases, geographical sub-species, wild state, from the rock-pigeon

@sen223    I then crossed one of the mongrel barb-fantails with a mongrel barb-spot, and they produced a bird of as beautiful a blue colour, with the white loins, double black wing-bar, and barred and white-edged tail-feathers, as any wild rock-pigeon!

              " (extract-fr) part 4 of  about: each other, domestic breeds, other cases, geographical sub-species, wild state, from the rock-pigeon

