              " (extract-fr) part 5 of  about: successive generations, domestic animals, slight differences, from the rock-pigeon

@sen238    Secondly, that although an English carrier or a short-faced tumbler differs immensely in certain characters from the rock-pigeon, yet that by comparing the several sub-breeds of these two races, more especially those brought from distant countries, we can make, between them and the rock-pigeon, an almost perfect series; so we can in some other cases, but not with all the breeds.

              " (extract-fr) part 5 of  about: successive generations, domestic animals, slight differences, from the rock-pigeon

@sen239    Thirdly, those characters which are mainly distinctive of each breed are in each eminently variable, for instance, the wattle and length of beak of the carrier, the shortness of that of the tumbler, and the number of tail-feathers in the fantail; and the explanation of this fact will be obvious when we treat of selection.

              " (extract-fr) part 5 of  about: successive generations, domestic animals, slight differences, from the rock-pigeon

@sen241    They have been domesticated for thousands of years in several quarters of the world; the earliest known record of pigeons is in the fifth Aegyptian dynasty, about 3000 B.

              " (extract-fr) part 5 of  about: successive generations, domestic animals, slight differences, from the rock-pigeon

@sen244    In the time of the Romans, as we hear from Pliny, immense prices were given for pigeons; "nay, they are come to this pass, that they can reckon up their pedigree and race." Pigeons were much valued by Akber Khan in India, about the year 1600; never less than 20,000 pigeons were taken with the court.

              " (extract-fr) part 5 of  about: successive generations, domestic animals, slight differences, from the rock-pigeon

@sen245    "The monarchs of Iran and Turan sent him some very rare birds;" and, continues the courtly historian, "His Majesty, by crossing the breeds, which method was never practised before, has improved them astonishingly." About this same period the Dutch were as eager about pigeons as were the old Romans.

              " (extract-fr) part 5 of  about: successive generations, domestic animals, slight differences, from the rock-pigeon

@sen246    The paramount importance of these considerations in explaining the immense amount of variation which pigeons have undergone, will likewise be obvious when we treat of selection.

