 :: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level ::

@sen945    A large number of individuals, by giving a better chance within any given period for the appearance of profitable variations, will compensate for a lesser amount of variability in each individual, and is, I believe, a highly important element of success.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen946    Though nature grants long periods of time for the work of natural selection, she does not grant an indefinite period; for as all organic beings are striving to seize on each place in the economy of nature, if any one species does not become modified and improved in a corresponding degree with its competitors it will be exterminated.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen947    Unless favourable variations be inherited by some at least of the offspring, nothing can be effected by natural selection.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen948    The tendency to reversion may often check or prevent the work; but as this tendency has not prevented man from forming by selection numerous domestic races, why should it prevail against natural selection?

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen949   In the case of methodical selection, a breeder selects for some definite object, and if the individuals be allowed freely to intercross, his work will completely fail.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen950    But when many men, without intending to alter the breed, have a nearly common standard of perfection, and all try to procure and breed from the best animals, improvement surely but slowly follows from this unconscious process of selection, notwithstanding that there is no separation of selected individuals.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen951    Thus it will be under nature; for within a confined area, with some place in the natural polity not perfectly occupied, all the individuals varying in the right direction, though in different degrees, will tend to be preserved.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen952    But if the area be large, its several districts will almost certainly present different conditions of life; and then, if the same species undergoes modification in different districts, the newly formed varieties will intercross on the confines of each.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen953    But we shall see in the sixth chapter that intermediate varieties, inhabiting intermediate districts, will in the long run generally be supplanted by one of the adjoining varieties.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen954    Intercrossing will chiefly affect those animals which unite for each birth and wander much, and which do not breed at a very quick rate.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen955    Hence with animals of this nature, for instance birds, varieties will generally be confined to separated countries; and this I find to be the case.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen956    With hermaphrodite organisms which cross only occasionally, and likewise with animals which unite for each birth, but which wander little and can increase at a rapid rate, a new and improved variety might be quickly formed on any one spot, and might there maintain itself in a body and afterward spread, so that the individuals of the new variety would chiefly cross together.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen958   Even with animals which unite for each birth, and which do not propagate rapidly, we must not assume that free intercrossing would always eliminate the effects of natural selection; for I can bring forward a considerable body of facts showing that within the same area two varieties of the same animal may long remain distinct, from haunting different stations, from breeding at slightly different seasons, or from the individuals of each variety preferring to pair together.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen959   Intercrossing plays a very important part in nature by keeping the individuals of the same species, or of the same variety, true and uniform in character.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen960    It will obviously thus act far more efficiently with those animals which unite for each birth; but, as already stated, we have reason to believe that occasional intercrosses take place with all animals and plants.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen961    Even if these take place only at long intervals of time, the young thus produced will gain so much in vigour and fertility over the offspring from long-continued self-fertilisation, that they will have a better chance of surviving and propagating their kind; and thus in the long run the influence of crosses, even at rare intervals, will be great.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen962    With respect to organic beings extremely low in the scale, which do not propagate sexually, nor conjugate, and which cannot possibly intercross, uniformity of character can be retained by them under the same conditions of life, only through the principle of inheritance, and through natural selection which will destroy any individuals departing from the proper type.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen963    If the conditions of life change and the form undergoes modification, uniformity of character can be given to the modified offspring, solely by natural selection preserving similar favourable variations.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen964   Isolation also is an important element in the modification of species through natural selection.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen965    In a confined or isolated area, if not very large, the organic and inorganic conditions of life will generally be almost uniform; so that natural selection will tend to modify all the varying individuals of the same species in the same manner.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen967    Moritz Wagner has lately published an interesting essay on this subject, and has shown that the service rendered by isolation in preventing crosses between newly-formed varieties is probably greater even than I supposed.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen968    But from reasons already assigned I can by no means agree with this naturalist, that migration and isolation are necessary elements for the formation of new species.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen969    The importance of isolation is likewise great in preventing, after any physical change in the conditions, such as of climate, elevation of the land, etc.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen972    If, however, an isolated area be very small, either from being surrounded by barriers, or from having very peculiar physical conditions, the total number of the inhabitants will be small; and this will retard the production of new species through natural selection, by decreasing the chances of favourable variations arising.

