@sen976    It likewise tends to increase the direct action of the physical conditions of life, in relation to the constitution of each organism.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen977   If we turn to nature to test the truth of these remarks, and look at any small isolated area, such as an oceanic island, although the number of the species inhabiting it is small, as we shall see in our chapter on Geographical Distribution; yet of these species a very large proportion are endemic,--that is, have been produced there and nowhere else in the world.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen978    Hence an oceanic island at first sight seems to have been highly favourable for the production of new species.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen979    But we may thus deceive ourselves, for to ascertain whether a small isolated area, or a large open area like a continent, has been most favourable for the production of new organic forms, we ought to make the comparison within equal times; and this we are incapable of doing.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen980   Although isolation is of great importance in the production of new species, on the whole I am inclined to believe that largeness of area is still more important, especially for the production of species which shall prove capable of enduring for a long period, and of spreading widely.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen981    Throughout a great and open area, not only will there be a better chance of favourable variations, arising from the large number of individuals of the same species there supported, but the conditions of life are much more complex from the large number of already existing species; and if some of these many species become modified and improved, others will have to be improved in a corresponding degree, or they will be exterminated.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen982    Each new form, also, as soon as it has been much improved, will be able to spread over the open and continuous area, and will thus come into competition with many other forms.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen983    Moreover, great areas, though now continuous, will often, owing to former oscillations of level, have existed in a broken condition, so that the good effects of isolation will generally, to a certain extent, have concurred.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen984    Finally, I conclude that, although small isolated areas have been in some respects highly favourable for the production of new species, yet that the course of modification will generally have been more rapid on large areas; and what is more important, that the new forms produced on large areas, which already have been victorious over many competitors, will be those that will spread most widely, and will give rise to the greatest number of new varieties and species.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen985    They will thus play a more important part in the changing history of the organic world.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen986   In accordance with this view, we can, perhaps, understand some facts which will be again alluded to in our chapter on Geographical Distribution; for instance, the fact of the productions of the smaller continent of Australia now yielding before those of the larger Europaeo-Asiatic area.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

@sen989    Hence, we can understand how it is that the flora of Madeira, according to Oswald Heer, resembles to a certain extent the extinct tertiary flora of Europe.

              " (extract-fr) part 21 of  about: same species, new species, natural selection, confined area, old inhabitants, less severe, through natural selection, conditions of life, intervals of time, oscillations of level

 :: each other, other animals, second chapter, from each other, divergence of character, increase in number ::

