@sen1381    Geoffroy St. Hilaire, both with varieties and species, that when any part or organ is repeated many times in the same individual [as the vertebrae in snakes, and the stamens in polyandrous flowers] the number is variable; whereas the number of the same part or organ, when it occurs in lesser numbers, is constant.

              " (extract-fr) part 30 of  about: other hand, same genus, natural selection, one hand, through natural selection

@sen1383    As "vegetative repetition," to use Professor Owen's expression, is a sign of low organisation; the foregoing statements accord with the common opinion of naturalists, that beings which stand low in the scale of nature are more variable than those which are higher. I presume that lowness here means that the several parts of the organisation have been but little specialised for particular functions; and as long as the same part has to perform diversified work, we can perhaps see why it should remain variable, that is, why natural selection should not have preserved or rejected each little deviation of form so carefully as when the part has to serve for some one special purpose. In the same way that a knife which has to cut all sorts of things may be of almost any shape; whilst a tool for some particular purpose must be of some particular shape. Natural selection, it should never be forgotten, can act solely through and for the advantage of each being.

              " (extract-fr) part 30 of  about: other hand, same genus, natural selection, one hand, through natural selection

@sen1384   Rudimentary parts, as is generally admitted, are apt to be highly variable.

