@sen1428    To explain by a simple example what is meant: if in a large genus of plants some species had blue flowers and some had red, the colour would be only a specific character, and no one would be surprised at one of the blue species varying into red, or conversely; but if all the species had blue flowers, the colour would become a generic character, and its variation would be a more unusual circumstance.

              " (extract-fr) part 31 of  about: distinct species, common progenitor, same species, same genus, independently created, each other, one species, sexual characters, natural selection, generic characters, our theory, same group, specific characters, through natural selection, secondary sexual characters, group of species, any one species, resemble each other

@sen1429    I have chosen this example because the explanation which most naturalists would advance is not here applicable, namely, that specific characters are more variable than generic, because they are taken from parts of less physiological importance than those commonly used for classing genera.

              " (extract-fr) part 31 of  about: distinct species, common progenitor, same species, same genus, independently created, each other, one species, sexual characters, natural selection, generic characters, our theory, same group, specific characters, through natural selection, secondary sexual characters, group of species, any one species, resemble each other

@sen1431    It would be almost superfluous to adduce evidence in support of the statement, that ordinary specific characters are more variable than generic; but with respect to important characters, I have repeatedly noticed in works on natural history, that when an author remarks with surprise that some important organ or part, which is generally very constant throughout a large group of species, DIFFERS considerably in closely-allied species, it is often VARIABLE in the individuals of the same species.

