@sen2092    If so, it will hardly be denied that the points might have been converted through variation and natural selection into lamellae as well-developed as those of the Egyptian goose, in which case they would have been used both for seizing objects and for sifting the water; then into lamellae like those of the domestic duck; and so onward, until they became as well constructed as those of the shoveller, in which case they would have served exclusively as a sifting apparatus.

              " (extract-fr) part 46 of  about: other hand, this case, one side, vertical position, early youth, lateral fins, right side, habits of life

