@sen2140    Mivart in every detail, remarks on this structure: "It is impossible to believe that in any number of ages the first slight incipient tendency to grasp could preserve the lives of the individuals possessing it, or favour their chance of having and of rearing offspring." But there is no necessity for any such belief.

              " (extract-fr) part 47 of  about: this case, marsupial form

@sen2143    Professor Henslow kept in confinement some harvest mice [Mus messorius] which do not possess a structurally prehensive tail; but he frequently observed that they curled their tails round the branches of a bush placed in the cage, and thus aided themselves in climbing.

