              " (extract-fr) part 54 of  about: securely reared, bare ground, three days

@sen2439    In some cases compulsory habit alone has sufficed to produce inherited mental changes; in other cases compulsory habit has done nothing, and all has been the result of selection, pursued both methodically and unconsciously; but in most cases habit and selection have probably concurred.

              " (extract-fr) part 54 of  about: securely reared, bare ground, three days

@sen2441   We shall, perhaps, best understand how instincts in a state of nature have become modified by selection by considering a few cases.

              " (extract-fr) part 54 of  about: securely reared, bare ground, three days

@sen2442    I will select only three, namely, the instinct which leads the cuckoo to lay her eggs in other birds' nests; the slave-making instinct of certain ants; and the cell-making power of the hive-bee: these two latter instincts have generally and justly been ranked by naturalists as the most wonderful of all known instincts.

              " (extract-fr) part 54 of  about: securely reared, bare ground, three days

@sen2444   It is supposed by some naturalists that the more immediate cause of the instinct of the cuckoo is that she lays her eggs, not daily, but at intervals of two or three days; so that, if she were to make her own nest and sit on her own eggs, those first laid would have to be left for some time unincubated or there would be eggs and young birds of different ages in the same nest.

              " (extract-fr) part 54 of  about: securely reared, bare ground, three days

@sen2447    It has been both asserted and denied that the American cuckoo occasionally lays her eggs in other birds' nests; but I have lately heard from Dr. Merrill, of Iowa, that he once found in Illinois a young cuckoo, together with a young jay in the nest of a blue jay [Garrulus cristatus]; and as both were nearly full feathered, there could be no mistake in their identification. I could also give several instances of various birds which have been known occasionally to lay their eggs in other birds' nests.

              " (extract-fr) part 54 of  about: securely reared, bare ground, three days

@sen2448    Now let us suppose that the ancient progenitor of our European cuckoo had the habits of the American cuckoo, and that she occasionally laid an egg in another bird's nest. If the old bird profited by this occasional habit through being enabled to emigrate earlier or through any other cause; or if the young were made more vigorous by advantage being taken of the mistaken instinct of another species than when reared by their own mother, encumbered as she could hardly fail to be by having eggs and young of different ages at the same time, then the old birds or the fostered young would gain an advantage. And analogy would lead us to believe that the young thus reared would be apt to follow by inheritance the occasional and aberrant habit of their mother, and in their turn would be apt to lay their eggs in other birds' nests, and thus be more successful in rearing their young.

              " (extract-fr) part 54 of  about: securely reared, bare ground, three days

@sen2455    Ramsay's observations, we have learned something about three Australian species, which lay their eggs in other birds' nests.

              " (extract-fr) part 54 of  about: securely reared, bare ground, three days

