              " (extract-fr) part 87 of  about: allied species, new zealand, same country, open ocean, throughout the world

@sen3929    Some of these species are so distinct, that we cannot suppose that there has been time since the commencement of the last Glacial period for their migration and subsequent modification to the necessary degree.

              " (extract-fr) part 87 of  about: allied species, new zealand, same country, open ocean, throughout the world

@sen3930    The facts seem to indicate that distinct species belonging to the same genera have migrated in radiating lines from a common centre; and I am inclined to look in the southern, as in the northern hemisphere, to a former and warmer period, before the commencement of the last Glacial period, when the Antarctic lands, now covered with ice, supported a highly peculiar and isolated flora.

              " (extract-fr) part 87 of  about: allied species, new zealand, same country, open ocean, throughout the world

@sen3931    It may be suspected that before this flora was exterminated during the last Glacial epoch, a few forms had been already widely dispersed to various points of the southern hemisphere by occasional means of transport, and by the aid, as halting-places, of now sunken islands.

              " (extract-fr) part 87 of  about: allied species, new zealand, same country, open ocean, throughout the world

@sen3932    Thus the southern shores of America, Australia, and New Zealand may have become slightly tinted by the same peculiar forms of life.

              " (extract-fr) part 87 of  about: allied species, new zealand, same country, open ocean, throughout the world

@sen3933   Sir C. Lyell in a striking passage has speculated, in language almost identical with mine, on the effects of great alternations of climate throughout the world on geographical distribution.

              " (extract-fr) part 87 of  about: allied species, new zealand, same country, open ocean, throughout the world

@sen3935    Croll's conclusion that successive Glacial periods in the one hemisphere coincide with warmer periods in the opposite hemisphere, together with the admission of the slow modification of species, explains a multitude of facts in the distribution of the same and of the allied forms of life in all parts of the globe. The living waters have flowed during one period from the north and during another from the south, and in both cases have reached the equator; but the stream of life has flowed with greater force from the north than in the opposite direction, and has consequently more freely inundated the south. As the tide leaves its drift in horizontal lines, rising higher on the shores where the tide rises highest, so have the living waters left their living drift on our mountain summits, in a line gently rising from the Arctic lowlands to a great latitude under the equator. The various beings thus left stranded may be compared with savage races of man, driven up and surviving in the mountain fastnesses of almost every land, which serves as a record, full of interest to us, of the former inhabitants of the surrounding lowlands.

              " (extract-fr) part 87 of  about: allied species, new zealand, same country, open ocean, throughout the world

@sen3939   As lakes and river-systems are separated from each other by barriers of land, it might have been thought that fresh-water productions would not have ranged widely within the same country, and as the sea is apparently a still more formidable barrier, that they would never have extended to distant countries.

              " (extract-fr) part 87 of  about: allied species, new zealand, same country, open ocean, throughout the world

@sen3941    Not only have many fresh-water species, belonging to different classes, an enormous range, but allied species prevail in a remarkable manner throughout the world.

              " (extract-fr) part 87 of  about: allied species, new zealand, same country, open ocean, throughout the world

@sen3944   But the wide ranging power of fresh-water productions can, I think, in most cases be explained by their having become fitted, in a manner highly useful to them, for short and frequent migrations from pond to pond, or from stream to stream, within their own countries; and liability to wide dispersal would follow from this capacity as an almost necessary consequence.

              " (extract-fr) part 87 of  about: allied species, new zealand, same country, open ocean, throughout the world

@sen3946    It was formerly believed that the same fresh-water species never existed on two continents distant from each other.

              " (extract-fr) part 87 of  about: allied species, new zealand, same country, open ocean, throughout the world

