@sen4500   These two principles, namely, that slight variations generally appear at a not very early period of life, and are inherited at a corresponding not early period, explain, as I believe, all the above specified leading facts in embryology.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4501    But first let us look to a few analogous cases in our domestic varieties.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4502    Some authors who have written on Dogs maintain that the greyhound and bull-dog, though so different, are really closely allied varieties, descended from the same wild stock, hence I was curious to see how far their puppies differed from each other.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4503    I was told by breeders that they differed just as much as their parents, and this, judging by the eye, seemed almost to be the case; but on actually measuring the old dogs and their six-days-old puppies, I found that the puppies had not acquired nearly their full amount of proportional difference.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4506    I carefully measured the proportions [but will not here give the details] of the beak, width of mouth, length of nostril and of eyelid, size of feet and length of leg, in the wild parent species, in pouters, fantails, runts, barbs, dragons, carriers, and tumblers.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4507    Now, some of these birds, when mature, differ in so extraordinary a manner in the length and form of beak, and in other characters, that they would certainly have been ranked as distinct genera if found in a state of nature.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4510    But there was one remarkable exception to this rule, for the young of the short-faced tumbler differed from the young of the wild rock-pigeon, and of the other breeds, in almost exactly the same proportions as in the adult stage.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4515    And the cases just given, more especially that of the pigeons, show that the characteristic differences which have been accumulated by man's selection, and which give value to his breeds, do not generally appear at a very early period of life, and are inherited at a corresponding not early period. But the case of the short-faced tumbler, which when twelve hours old possessed its proper characters, proves that this is not the universal rule; for here the characteristic differences must either have appeared at an earlier period than usual, or, if not so, the differences must have been inherited, not at a corresponding, but at an earlier age.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4516   Now, let us apply these two principles to species in a state of nature.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4517    Let us take a group of birds, descended from some ancient form and modified through natural selection for different habits.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4518    Then, from the many slight successive variations having supervened in the several species at a not early age, and having been inherited at a corresponding age, the young will have been but little modified, and they will still resemble each other much more closely than do the adults, just as we have seen with the breeds of the pigeon.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4520    The fore-limbs, for instance, which once served as legs to a remote progenitor, may have become, through a long course of modification, adapted in one descendant to act as hands, in another as paddles, in another as wings; but on the above two principles the fore-limbs will not have been much modified in the embryos of these several forms; although in each form the fore-limb will differ greatly in the adult state.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4521    Whatever influence long continued use or disuse may have had in modifying the limbs or other parts of any species, this will chiefly or solely have affected it when nearly mature, when it was compelled to use its full powers to gain its own living; and the effects thus produced will have been transmitted to the offspring at a corresponding nearly mature age.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4522    Thus the young will not be modified, or will be modified only in a slight degree, through the effects of the increased use or disuse of parts.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4523   With some animals the successive variations may have supervened at a very early period of life, or the steps may have been inherited at an earlier age than that at which they first occurred.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4524    In either of these cases the young or embryo will closely resemble the mature parent-form, as we have seen with the short-faced tumbler.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4525    And this is the rule of development in certain whole groups, or in certain sub-groups alone, as with cuttle-fish, land-shells, fresh-water crustaceans, spiders, and some members of the great class of insects.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4526    With respect to the final cause of the young in such groups not passing through any metamorphosis, we can see that this would follow from the following contingencies: namely, from the young having to provide at a very early age for their own wants, and from their following the same habits of life with their parents; for in this case it would be indispensable for their existence that they should be modified in the same manner as their parents.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4527    Again, with respect to the singular fact that many terrestrial and fresh-water animals do not undergo any metamorphosis, while marine members of the same groups pass through various transformations, Fritz Muller has suggested that the process of slowly modifying and adapting an animal to live on the land or in fresh water, instead of in the sea, would be greatly simplified by its not passing through any larval stage; for it is not probable that places well adapted for both the larval and mature stages, under such new and greatly changed habits of life, would commonly be found unoccupied or ill-occupied by other organisms.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4528    In this case the gradual acquirement at an earlier and earlier age of the adult structure would be favoured by natural selection; and all traces of former metamorphoses would finally be lost.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4529   If, on the other hand, it profited the young of an animal to follow habits of life slightly different from those of the parent-form, and consequently to be constructed on a slightly different plan, or if it profited a larva already different from its parent to change still further, then, on the principle of inheritance at corresponding ages, the young or the larvae might be rendered by natural selection more and more different from their parents to any conceivable extent.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4530    Differences in the larva might, also, become correlated with successive stages of its development; so that the larva, in the first stage, might come to differ greatly from the larva in the second stage, as is the case with many animals.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4533   From the remarks just made we can see how by changes of structure in the young, in conformity with changed habits of life, together with inheritance at corresponding ages, animals might come to pass through stages of development, perfectly distinct from the primordial condition of their adult progenitors.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4538    These larvae are hatched in the nests of bees; and when the male bees emerge from their burrows, in the spring, which they do before the females, the larvae spring on them, and afterwards crawl on to the females while paired with the males.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4540    Afterwards they undergo a complete change; their eyes disappear; their legs and antennae become rudimentary, and they feed on honey; so that they now more closely resemble the ordinary larvae of insects; ultimately they undergo a further transformation, and finally emerge as the perfect beetle.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4541    Now, if an insect, undergoing transformations like those of the Sitaris, were to become the progenitor of a whole new class of insects, the course of development of the new class would be widely different from that of our existing insects; and the first larval stage certainly would not represent the former condition of any adult and ancient form.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4542   On the other hand it is highly probable that with many animals the embryonic or larval stages show us, more or less completely, the condition of the progenitor of the whole group in its adult state.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4543    In the great class of the Crustacea, forms wonderfully distinct from each other, namely, suctorial parasites, cirripedes, entomostraca, and even the malacostraca, appear at first as larvae under the nauplius-form; and as these larvae live and feed in the open sea, and are not adapted for any peculiar habits of life, and from other reasons assigned by Fritz Muller, it is probable that at some very remote period an independent adult animal, resembling the Nauplius, existed, and subsequently produced, along several divergent lines of descent, the above-named great Crustacean groups.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

@sen4544    So again, it is probable, from what we know of the embryos of mammals, birds, fishes and reptiles, that these animals are the modified descendants of some ancient progenitor, which was furnished in its adult state with branchiae, a swim-bladder, four fin-like limbs, and a long tail, all fitted for an aquatic life.

              " (extract-fr) part 100 of  about: other hand, natural selection, adult state, period of life, facts in embryology

 :: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology ::

@sen4545   As all the organic beings, extinct and recent, which have ever lived, can be arranged within a few great classes; and as all within each class have, according to our theory, been connected together by fine gradations, the best, and, if our collections were nearly perfect, the only possible arrangement, would be genealogical; descent being the hidden bond of connexion which naturalists have been seeking under the term of the Natural System.

              " (extract-fr) part 101 of  about: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology

@sen4546    On this view we can understand how it is that, in the eyes of most naturalists, the structure of the embryo is even more important for classification than that of the adult.

              " (extract-fr) part 101 of  about: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology

@sen4547    In two or more groups of animals, however much they may differ from each other in structure and habits in their adult condition, if they pass through closely similar embryonic stages, we may feel assured that they are all descended from one parent-form, and are therefore closely related.

              " (extract-fr) part 101 of  about: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology

@sen4548    Thus, community in embryonic structure reveals community of descent; but dissimilarity in embryonic development does not prove discommunity of descent, for in one of two groups the developmental stages may have been suppressed, or may have been so greatly modified through adaptation to new habits of life as to be no longer recognisable.

              " (extract-fr) part 101 of  about: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology

@sen4549    Even in groups, in which the adults have been modified to an extreme degree, community of origin is often revealed by the structure of the larvae; we have seen, for instance, that cirripedes, though externally so like shell-fish, are at once known by their larvae to belong to the great class of crustaceans.

              " (extract-fr) part 101 of  about: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology

@sen4550    As the embryo often shows us more or less plainly the structure of the less modified and ancient progenitor of the group, we can see why ancient and extinct forms so often resemble in their adult state the embryos of existing species of the same class.

              " (extract-fr) part 101 of  about: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology

@sen4551    Agassiz believes this to be a universal law of nature; and we may hope hereafter to see the law proved true.

              " (extract-fr) part 101 of  about: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology

@sen4552    It can, however, be proved true only in those cases in which the ancient state of the progenitor of the group has not been wholly obliterated, either by successive variations having supervened at a very early period of growth, or by such variations having been inherited at an earlier age than that at which they first appeared.

              " (extract-fr) part 101 of  about: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology

@sen4553    It should also be borne in mind, that the law may be true, but yet, owing to the geological record not extending far enough back in time, may remain for a long period, or for ever, incapable of demonstration.

              " (extract-fr) part 101 of  about: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology

@sen4554    The law will not strictly hold good in those cases in which an ancient form became adapted in its larval state to some special line of life, and transmitted the same larval state to a whole group of descendants; for such larval state will not resemble any still more ancient form in its adult state.

              " (extract-fr) part 101 of  about: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology

@sen4555   Thus, as it seems to me, the leading facts in embryology, which are second to none in importance, are explained on the principle of variations in the many descendants from some one ancient progenitor, having appeared at a not very early period of life, and having been inherited at a corresponding period.

              " (extract-fr) part 101 of  about: same species, rudimentary organs, same class, natural system, natural selection, embryonic condition, corresponding period, period of life, state of things, facts in embryology

@sen4556    Embryology rises greatly in interest, when we look at the embryo as a picture, more or less obscured, of the progenitor, either in its adult or larval state, of all the members of the same great class.

