@sen4602    We have plenty of cases of rudimentary organs in our domestic productions, as the stump of a tail in tailless breeds, the vestige of an ear in earless breeds of sheep--the reappearance of minute dangling horns in hornless breeds of cattle, more especially, according to Youatt, in young animals--and the state of the whole flower in the cauliflower.

              " (extract-fr) part 102 of  about: distinct species, same species, natural selection, slight variations, early age, common parents, this difficulty, from common parents

@sen4603    We often see rudiments of various parts in monsters; but I doubt whether any of these cases throw light on the origin of rudimentary organs in a state of nature, further than by showing that rudiments can be produced; for the balance of evidence clearly indicates that species under nature do not undergo great and abrupt changes.

              " (extract-fr) part 102 of  about: distinct species, same species, natural selection, slight variations, early age, common parents, this difficulty, from common parents

@sen4604    But we learn from the study of our domestic productions that the disuse of parts leads to their reduced size; and that the result is inherited.

