@sen4737   As each species tends by its geometrical rate of reproduction to increase inordinately in number; and as the modified descendants of each species will be enabled to increase by as much as they become more diversified in habits and structure, so as to be able to seize on many and widely different places in the economy of nature, there will be a constant tendency in natural selection to preserve the most divergent offspring of any one species.

              " (extract-fr) part 105 of  about: allied species, independently created, natural selection, permanent varieties, same continent, secondary laws, great classes, dominant forms, through natural selection, conditions of life, subordinate to groups, theory of creation, acts of creation, few great classes

